A volunteer outbreak response group at a county health department is staffed by part-time student investigators and a few public health interns, and they need a shared workspace for managing local outbreak investigation each time a cluster gets reported. When a new outbreak is opened — say, a suspected foodborne illness from a community event — the lead investigator creates a case in the app, drafts the case definition with input from a supervising epidemiologist, and shares a link with the team. Team members can each pick up a few interviews, recording exposure histories from suspected cases in a structured questionnaire that the team has built collaboratively to fit this outbreak. As entries come in, the app tallies a working line list and surfaces the common exposures across cases, supporting the team in conducting an internal case-control study design analysis: pulling controls from non-ill attendees of the same event, computing odds ratios for each candidate exposure, and surfacing the strongest measures of association. The app should let the team add notes about confounding factors — multiple foods served together, attendees who arrived late — and flag selection bias risks in how controls were chosen. Each evening the lead investigator publishes an updated outbreak status note that everyone can comment on, and the supervising epidemiologist can approve the case definition for any external sharing. The investigation closes when the team agrees on a primary hypothesis, with a final write-up exported as a structured report that follows the outbreak investigation conventions taught in introductory epidemiology — descriptive epidemiology, hypothesis generation, analytic phase, control measures, and lessons learned for future disease surveillance.